an infinite series here.

00:00:02.305 --> 00:00:05.113
Negative one to the n plus
one over the square root of n.

00:00:05.113 --> 00:00:06.630
I always like to visualize this

00:00:06.630 --> 00:00:08.276
a little bit more, expand it out.

00:00:08.276 --> 00:00:10.685
So when n equals one the
first term is negative one

00:00:10.685 --> 00:00:12.461
to the second power, so
it's going to be positive.

00:00:12.461 --> 00:00:14.387
It's going to be one
over one and so it's one

00:00:14.387 --> 00:00:16.929
minus one over the square root of two

00:00:16.929 --> 00:00:19.575
plus one over the square root of three

00:00:19.575 --> 00:00:22.115
minus one over the square
root of four and then

00:00:22.115 --> 00:00:25.379
plus, minus, and we just go
on and on and on forever.

00:00:26.002 --> 00:00:28.810
Now when we looked at convergence tests

00:00:28.810 --> 00:00:32.218
for infinite series we
saw things like this.

00:00:32.235 --> 00:00:35.102
This passes the alternating series test

00:00:35.102 --> 00:00:37.015
and so we know that this converges.

00:00:37.015 --> 00:00:40.063
Let's say it converges to some value S.

00:00:40.473 --> 00:00:42.401
But what we're concerned
with in this video is

00:00:42.401 --> 00:00:44.923
not whether or not this
converges, but estimating

00:00:44.923 --> 00:00:47.436
what this actually converges to.

00:00:47.436 --> 00:00:51.197
We know that we can estimate
this by taking a partial sum.

00:00:51.827 --> 00:00:55.844
Let's say S sub k, this is the
first k terms right over here

00:00:55.844 --> 00:00:57.561
and then you're going to have a remainder,

00:00:57.561 --> 00:01:01.953
so plus the remainder after
you've taken the first k terms.

00:01:01.953 --> 00:01:04.882
So this actually starts
with the k plus first term.

00:01:05.283 --> 00:01:07.335
And so what I am concerned
about or what I want

00:01:07.335 --> 00:01:10.843
to figure out is what's the
minimum number of terms,

00:01:10.843 --> 00:01:15.030
what's the minimum k here
so that my remainder,

00:01:15.030 --> 00:01:17.666
so that the absolute value of my remainder

00:01:17.666 --> 00:01:22.666
is less than or equal to 0.001.

00:01:23.467 --> 00:01:25.164
And I encourage you to
pause the video based

00:01:25.164 --> 00:01:26.403
on what we've seen in previous

00:01:26.403 --> 00:01:28.981
alternating series estimation situations

00:01:28.981 --> 00:01:30.663
to see if you can figure this out.

00:01:31.620 --> 00:01:35.552
Alright I'm assuming
you've had a go at it.

00:01:35.552 --> 00:01:39.210
So let's just remind ourselves
what R sub k looks like.

00:01:39.210 --> 00:01:44.210
So R sub k is going to start
with the k plus first term.

00:01:46.211 --> 00:01:50.371
So it's going to be negative
one k plus one plus one,

00:01:50.371 --> 00:01:54.483
so it's negative one
to the k plus two over

00:01:54.483 --> 00:01:59.483
the square root of k plus one.

00:02:02.415 --> 00:02:06.343
And then the next term
I can just write plus

00:02:06.343 --> 00:02:10.465
negative one to the k plus three over

00:02:10.465 --> 00:02:14.211
the square root of k plus two.

00:02:14.235 --> 00:02:17.198
And it's just going to go
on and on and on like that.

00:02:17.732 --> 00:02:20.683
Now what we know already or
what we've seen an example of

00:02:20.683 --> 00:02:23.242
and we'll verify it or at
least conceptual verification

00:02:23.242 --> 00:02:27.872
for us at the end of this
video is the absolute

00:02:27.872 --> 00:02:32.872
value of this entire sum
is going to be less than

00:02:34.022 --> 00:02:36.397
the absolute value of the first term.

00:02:36.397 --> 00:02:37.842
So let me write that down.

00:02:37.842 --> 00:02:42.842
The absolute value of this
entire remainder R sub k...

00:02:42.881 --> 00:02:45.280
And some people refer
to this as kind of the

00:02:45.280 --> 00:02:48.232
alternating series remainder property

00:02:48.232 --> 00:02:49.998
or whatever you want to call it.

00:02:49.998 --> 00:02:52.184
But the absolute value
of this entire thing

00:02:52.184 --> 00:02:55.671
is going to be less than or
equal to the absolute value

00:02:55.671 --> 00:03:00.671
of the first term, negative
one to the k plus two

00:03:00.848 --> 00:03:04.822
over the square root of k plus one.

00:03:04.822 --> 00:03:08.631
And of course we want that to
be less than one thousandth.

00:03:08.631 --> 00:03:13.631
So that needs to be less
than or equal to 0.001.

00:03:14.786 --> 00:03:17.480
And so now this setup
right over here inspires

00:03:17.480 --> 00:03:19.752
you, I once again encourage
you to pause the video

00:03:19.752 --> 00:03:21.574
